Part I - (Ford GoBike System Data)¶

by (Josphine Ijoni)¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

I will be understanding the data structure and brainstorming some more questions, conducting preliminary data wrangling, such as changing data types of specific columns, and make sure you don't have too many missing values I will be using the Question-Visualization-Observations" framework. which involves asking a question from the data, creating a visualization to find answers, and then recording observations.And finally systematically exploring the data starting with Univariate, and moving on to Bivariate and Multivariate explorations. I also documented the flow of exploration in the markdown cells and recorded my conclusions on my main findings and reflected on the steps taken during the data exploration.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 fordbike rides in the dataset with 16 features (duration_sec,start_time,end_time,start_station_id, start_station_latitude,start_station_longitude,end_station_id,end_station_latitude,end_station_longitude,bike_id, member_birth_yea,member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip). Most variables are numeric in nature, but the variables,duration_sec, start_time,end_time, and member birthyear are ordered factor variables, having year starting from 1878 to 2001 and start_time and end_time these would need to be changed to datetime and int respectively, to give us the days of the week the rides took place,which could be from monday to sunday.The dataset also has alot of null values in member_birth_year,member_gender,end_station_id,end_station_name,start_station_name and start_station_id, these would be removed to give us a more descriptive data

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of interest in my dataset is the duration_sec,start_time,end_time and the member_birth_year.I am most interested in figuring out what category of member_birth_year enjoyed the most bike rides in the fordbikes dataset and what day of the week had the most bike rides.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that duration_sec,start_time and end_time will have the strongest effect on each biker's rides, duration_sec: the larger the duration, the higher the end_time, end_station_latitude and end_station_longitude . I also think that the other features such as the start_station_name,start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, user_type,member_birth_year,member_gender,bike_share_for_all_trip, will have effects on the rides, though to a much smaller degree than the main effect of duration_sec.

Change start_day, end_day to ordinal variables¶¶

In [25]:
ordinal_var_dict = {'start_day': ['Mon', "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun"],
                    'end_day': ['Mon', "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat", "Sun"]}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    fordbikeRiders[var] = fordbikeRiders[var].astype(ordered_var)

The bike ride activity of the fordbikeRiders dataset is generally quite good, with the highest rides occurring on thursday with the highest count of more than 30,000 rides for both the start_day and end_day variables.What this means is that most professionals and working class members use the rides more for their daily activities on thursdays,even though the count on monday which is presumably the first working day of the week is 25,000 which is not up to thursdays count, I would assume some professionals work from home on this day,however the ride counts for saturday and sunday is the lowest with less than 15,000 rides happening meaning that an average bike rider would probably not ride a bike during the weekends unless it ia absolutely neccessary and ofcourse most of them do not work during the weekends.

The start_hour and end_hour plots are both with the highest count for start_hour at 8 and 17hours respectively.This means that riders resume their duty post for the days job at 8am and close from work at 17hour for each ride day.

The member_gender plot shows the male category having the highest count of above 120000 among the members who participated in the rides with a female count of 4000 rides.This also means most of the rides where done by male members who had to use the bikes during each work day and only 4000 females use the rides during work days.I also noticed other categories of member_gender

The user_type variable has the highest count of above 150,000 rides being from subscribers whereas only about 20,000 count of those rides where made by Customers, meaning most bike hires rides where made my mostly male subscribers.

The bike share for all trip plot shows a high bar count of 150,000 riders not sharing their bikes during each trip,while about 20,000 riders shared their bikes during the course of their rides.

As expected, the 'member_birth_year', 'start_hour', and 'end_hour' dimensions are all highly correlated with one another, and all of them are also highly correlated with duration_sec. Since duration_sec is a measure of ride count, it's not too surprising that the overall trend between duration and the three individual dimensions appears polynomial. In addition, since all the bike rides are done during the week, it makes sense that the 'member_birth_year', 'start_hour', and 'end_hour' variables would all move proportionally together.

Surprisingly, the correlation coefficient between duration_sec and end_station is not high, despite the fact that duration_sec has such a large range of values. This will be worth extra exploration in this section. Station_station and end_station_id don't have strong correlations with any other numeric variables in the dataset, and we see the moderate negative correlation hypothesized in the previous section. I won't perform any further analyses with these variables since they don't look like they'll be of much further interest.

# compute the logarithm of duration to make multivariate plotting easier
def logrithmicTrnsfm(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)
#diamonds['log_price'] = diamonds['price'].apply(log_trans)

def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating heat maps with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    the_yr = kwargs.pop('the_yr')
    the_durtion = kwargs.pop('the_durtion')
    if the_yr:
        bins_x = np.arange(1970, 2002+2, 2)
    else:
        bins_x = np.arange(0, 24)
    if the_durtion:
        bins_y = np.arange(1.5, 3.7+0.2, 0.2)
        plt.yticks(logrithmicTrnsfm(np.array([500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 10e3])), [500, '1k', '2k', '5k', "10k"])
        plt.hist2d(x, np.log10(y), bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 5)
    else:
        bins_y = np.arange(1970, 2002+2, 2)
        plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 5)

Conclusions¶

Having worked on this dataset exploration for forgo bike trip,I was able to observe how different Ford bike data variables and columns affect the duration of rides with bike use. discovered that the following factors, particularly when they are strengthened by one another, have an impact on how long bikers will use their bikes.I discovered that compared to other days, Sundays and Saturdays were more likely to have higher duration sec by start_day and bike share for all trip. The member_birth_year 2001 had the most bike rides in duration_sec from both user_types (customers and subscribers).I also observed that Customers have the greatest impact on how long the bike share programme lasts. They don't always use the bikeshare and they use the bikes for longer distances.

During the data exploration,I cleaned the data, splitted the days and hours from the datetime, changed some columns' data types, and removed unneccessary columns from the dataset in order to get the aforementioned conclusions. I then carried out monovariate exploration and visualization, followed by bivariate andlastly multivariate exploration and visualization of the dataset.
